Question 1 (i) response variable: volume of a tree; explanatory variable: diameter of a tree.

leaf=read.table("shortleaf.txt", header = T)
head(leaf)
##   Diam Vol
## 1  4.4 2.0
## 2  4.6 2.2
## 3  5.0 3.0
## 4  5.1 4.3
## 5  5.1 3.0
## 6  5.2 2.9
  1. Comment: There is a positive relation between diameters and volumes of trees, where larger the diameter of a tree, larger the volume of a tree. It is more like a positive exponetial curve rather than a linear figure.
plot(leaf$Diam, leaf$Vol, xlab="diameter", ylab="volume")
leaffit=lm(Vol~Diam, data=leaf)
abline(leaffit, col="blue")

  1. \[\hat{Volume}=-41.568+6.837Diameter\] The intercept is -41.57, which has no physical meaning because there is not negative value of volume when the diameter is 0. It is negative just because it is based on the least squared regression line. The slope is 6.837, which means for every 1 unit of diameter increases, the volume is predicted to increase 6.837 units.
summary(leaffit)

  1. Comment: From residual vs.fitted values, no evidence of departure from linearity. However, as suspected, variance of the residuals seems to be increasing with the predicted values (around from 85 to 120). Also, there might be an outlier.
library(MASS)
leaf_ri=studres(leaffit)
leaf_yihat=leaffit$fitted.values
plot(leaf_yihat,leaf_ri,ylab="Studentized Residuals",xlab="Fitted Values")
abline(h=0,col=2,lty=2)

Comment: From Normal Q-Q plot, it looks like the data is approximately normally distributed. Also, it looks like the distribution of residuals has a little bit thicker tails than what we would expect in a normal distribution. The middle part of the distribution is a little off the normal distribution.

But from the AD test, we found that p-value for normality is only 0.0003, which is really low. This can be due to the outlier at the right up corner.

qqnorm(leaf_ri)
qqline(leaf_ri)

library(nortest)
ad.test(studres(leaffit))
## 
##  Anderson-Darling normality test
## 
## data:  studres(leaffit)
## A = 1.6136, p-value = 0.0003451

Comment: From the Leverage plot, there are two points with leverage values higher than the expected cut-off. However, there is one point that has outstandingly large leverage value.

plot(hatvalues(leaffit), type="h", ylab="Leverage")
n=nrow(leaf)
p=length(coefficients(leaffit))
cutLev=2*p/n

  1. Comment: I think we can test for the transformation for response variable, explanatory variable and both when we are not sure which one will give us the best linear relation. But since there is no violation in the other assumptions: independence(trees grow independently), constant variacne(approximately increasing due to non linear), normality of the errors, we can start by transforming the predictor varible. I will choose to use the log transformation.

  2. Comment: Based on the plot, there is a positive trend between log of diameters and volumes of trees, where larger the log of diameter of a tree, larger the volume of a tree. The log transformation on the explanatory variable appears to lack linearity.

leaf1=data.frame(leaf,log(leaf$Diam))
names(leaf1)=c("Diam","Vol","lnDiam")
plot(leaf1$lnDiam,leaf1$Vol,xlab="Log(Diameter)",ylab="Volume",pch=20)
leaffit1=lm(Vol~lnDiam, data=leaf1)
abline(leaffit1,col=2)

  1. Comment: Based on the plot, there is a positive trend between diameters and log of volumes of trees, where larger the diameter of a tree, larger the log of volume of a tree. The log transformation on the reponse variable appears to lack linearity.
leaf2=data.frame(leaf1,log(leaf$Vol))
names(leaf2)=c("Diam","Vol","lnDiam","lnVol")
plot(leaf2$Diam,leaf2$lnVol, xlab="Diameter",ylab="Log(Volume)")
leaffit2=lm(leaf2$lnVol~leaf2$Diam)
abline(leaffit2, col="red")

Comment: Based on the plot, there is a positive lineartrend between log of diameters and log of volumes of trees, where larger the log of diameter of a tree, larger the log of volume of a tree. The log transformation on both the explanatory variable and the reponse variable appears to have linearity.

plot(leaf2$lnDiam,leaf2$lnVol, xlab="Log(Diameter)",ylab="Log(Volume)" )

The slope is 2.590, which means for every 1 unit of log of diameter increases, the log of volume is predicted to increase 2.590 units.
